ot original, is still early, most of it dating from 1604. A high proportion of its earliest book-stock, whether print or manuscript, still survives, and there is a wealth of documentation that makes it possible to chart the process of acquisition, especially the major donations of the Founder, Bishop Fox, and first President, John Claymond. And yet there is no modern, book-length study of the College Library. The present volume is intended to provide a scholarly but attractive and readable account of the Library from its conception in the mind of Richard Fox, to the appearance of its earliest surviving catalogue in 1589. It is extensively illustrated, highlighting the rarely-seen original bindings of the early books.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEarly printed bookszEnglandzOxford. 4aBibliography & Manuscripts. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aBook-stock.  aCatalogue.  aContemporary bindings.  aCorpus Christi College.  aFounder Bishop Fox.  aHistorical documentation.  aJohn Claymond.  aLibrary.  aOriginal bindings.  aOxford.  aPre-1600.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311143106240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178744261040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787442610423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787442610/original  a978-3-11-143106-2  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles